/** The Laws of FAFO, verbatim from asyncapi.yaml info.description (B7). */
export const LAWS_MARKDOWN = "**Causality as a Service.**\n\nA loving, event-driven reimagining of [FOAAS](https://github.com/tomdionysus/foaas).\nFOAAS was request/response: you asked to be told off, and you were told off,\nsynchronously, politely, within an HTTP round trip. A simpler time.\n\nFAFO does not work that way, because FAFO is not a query — it is a *causal process*.\nYou **fuck around** (a command, published as an event of intent) and you\n**find out** (a consequence, materialized asynchronously by the fabric).\nNobody has ever found out synchronously. The gap between the two is where\nall of engineering, law, and romance happens.\n\n### The Laws of FAFO (normative)\n\n1. **Conservation of Consequences.** Over any complete causal thread,\n   `∫ findout ≥ ∫ around`. The fabric MAY amplify; it MUST NOT attenuate.\n2. **Causal ordering.** Within an actor's partition, you never find out\n   *before* you fuck around. A strict happens-before relation is enforced.\n   Cross-actor ordering is undefined, which is why other people appear to\n   get away with things.\n3. **At-least-once delivery.** Consequences may be delivered more than once.\n   Consumers MUST deduplicate by `consequenceId`; the universe retries anyway.\n4. **Acknowledgement is not absolution.** Acking a consequence confirms\n   *receipt*, not *acceptance*, and does not prevent redelivery in dreams.\n5. **Partitioning is by actor.** Your consequences are keyed to you. They do\n   not rebalance to another consumer, no matter how the group is configured.\n6. **Infinite retention.** The findout log is immutable and retained forever.\n   There is no compaction. The internet remembers.\n7. **There is no staging environment.** All fucking around occurs in\n   production. See `servers`.\n";

